# > The purpose of this file is to store default
# > Compose rules for typing mathematical letter symbols
# > across multiple writing systems (meaning that, in this
# > particular case, this file will only contain the aforementioned
# > symbols if they can be input with non-alphabetical characters).
#
# [NOTE]: This diacritic will be represented as [U221D]
# ("âˆ", Proportional To) to give a better idea of
# the general intention this specific dead key has.
#
# [NOTE]: This file is part of the "Logic + Math Symbols" Dead Key,
# which has been separated to  better maintain
# different aspects pertaining to this expansive dead key.
#
# [Main source]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_operators_and_symbols_in_Unicode
#

# Mathematical Number Symbols (including Z-Notation)
#
# [NOTE]: The specific formatting of each character
# is determined by the following Perl-like regular expression
# applied to a LaTeX keyword (\{}):
#
# > regexp(Latin) = \\[FfMmSs]?[0-9]?{[a-zA-Z]}?[\*_|]?\s
#
# Where:
#   -> "F" = "f"        = Fraktur
#   -> "M" = "m"        = Monospace
#   -> "S"              = Script/Calligraphy
#   -> "s"              = Sans-serif
#   -> {[a-zA-Z]}       = Any alphabetical character enclosed in curly braces
#   -> "*"              = Final Bold (inspired by Markdown)
#   -> "_"              = Final Italic (inspired by Markdown)
#   -> "|"              = Double-Struck (aka Blackboard Bold)
#
# Any of these rules can be preceded by any dead key keysym if needed
# (and gets listed on any specific writing system file related to this diacritic).
#
# [Main source]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_Alphanumeric_Symbols
#
<U221D> <backslash> <0> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ"   # Bold 0
<U221D> <backslash> <0> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ˜"   # Double-Struck 0
<U221D> <backslash> <1> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ"   # Bold 1
<U221D> <backslash> <1> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ™"   # Double-Struck 1
<U221D> <backslash> <2> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ"   # Bold 2
<U221D> <backslash> <2> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸš"   # Double-Struck 2
<U221D> <backslash> <3> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ‘"   # Bold 3
<U221D> <backslash> <3> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ›"   # Double-Struck 3
<U221D> <backslash> <4> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ’"   # Bold 4
<U221D> <backslash> <4> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸœ"   # Double-Struck 4
<U221D> <backslash> <5> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ“"   # Bold 5
<U221D> <backslash> <5> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ"   # Double-Struck 5
<U221D> <backslash> <6> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ”"   # Bold 6
<U221D> <backslash> <6> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ"   # Double-Struck 6
<U221D> <backslash> <7> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ•"   # Bold 7
<U221D> <backslash> <7> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸŸ"   # Double-Struck 7
<U221D> <backslash> <8> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ–"   # Bold 8
<U221D> <backslash> <8> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ "   # Double-Struck 8
<U221D> <backslash> <9> <asterisk> <space>      : "ğŸ—"   # Bold 9
<U221D> <backslash> <9> <bar> <space>           : "ğŸ¡"   # Double-Struck 9
<U221D> <backslash> <colon> <bar> <space>       : "â¦‚"   # Z-Notation Type Colon
<U221D> <backslash> <semicolon> <space>         : "â¨¾"   # Z-Notation Relational Composition
<U221D> <backslash> <semicolon> <bar> <space>   : "â¨Ÿ"   # Z-Notation Schema Composition

